      {
        "id": "0ae8f218fe86512b96a4d977a4d265a6b7893187",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4965,
          "name": "Krzysztof Opasiak",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "k.opasiak@samsung.com",
          "username": "kopasiak"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-23 16:26:02.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n$ git checkout N/A\nerror: pathspec 'N/A' did not match any file(s) known to git.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "6d81aa57e71df6e5b5fe869f5e72259bf7b1a439",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4886,
          "name": "Petr Ospalý",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "p.ospaly@email.cz",
          "username": "p.ospaly"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-23 16:45:53.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis: git checkout N/A\n\nWhat is purpose of this command? If this directory is outside of git then echo N/A is not run at all - if it is in git directory then the original git rev-parse is used and because it will be valid it can be safely used. The output is used as a label - no one is interpreting that label if it is outside of git. So I dont see any relevancy with your artificial command - can you show me usage? That is like artificial example of erasing a random line from script and show it as a proof that the script is fundamentally flawed.\n\nI see this as a very simple change and the ratio of discussion vs the actual change is really bizarre :)\n\nIf I abondon this change then your artificial example will turn to this:\n\n$ git checkout\n\nSee missing argument and also the script stops working.\n\nPick your poison.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "d980bde8a7b599dab024ac67de8ee9c21789631c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-23 18:47:58.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n> This: git checkout N/A\n > \n > What is purpose of this command? If this directory is outside of\n > git then echo N/A is not run at all - if it is in git directory\n > then the original git rev-parse is used and because it will be\n > valid it can be safely used. The output is used as a label - no one\n > is interpreting that label if it is outside of git. So I dont see\n > any relevancy with your artificial command - can you show me usage?\n > That is like artificial example of erasing a random line from\n > script and show it as a proof that the script is fundamentally\n > flawed.\n > \n > I see this as a very simple change and the ratio of discussion vs\n > the actual change is really bizarre :)\n > \n > If I abondon this change then your artificial example will turn to\n > this:\n > \n > $ git checkout\n > \n > See missing argument and also the script stops working.\n > \n > Pick your poison.\n\nGuys, you both are right.\nWe have this same also elsewhere and it's good to find convention for this.\nHow about checking if in git repo and label it if in git repo?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "f4f2ee688177ff432cda25d197cb6471003f2a92",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4965,
          "name": "Krzysztof Opasiak",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "k.opasiak@samsung.com",
          "username": "kopasiak"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-23 20:48:38.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n@Samuli Silvius\nThat's exactly what I thought about while writing first comment.\nLet's add git-commit label only if we can generate it.\nNot to mention that it would be good to call the git command from script_dir as currently it works only if we call a script from inside of git repo. (And BTW if we call it from another git repo we will get hash from that repo not from offline installer one;)",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "afd221b88d244bdbd676e9d5ed6a07513274ad47",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4965,
          "name": "Krzysztof Opasiak",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "k.opasiak@samsung.com",
          "username": "kopasiak"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-23 20:49:58.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOh and another BTW it's a good practice to add + or -dirty at the end of hash if git status is unclean",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
